== Controversy == On the opening day of the conference the [[President of the United States]], [[Donald Trump]], caused controversy by asserting that Germany is beholden to Russia over its involvement in the [[Nord Stream]] gas pipeline project aimed at doubling energy imports from Russia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/2018/07/13/democrats-assail-trumps-remarks-on-germanys-reliance-on-russia-despite-kerry-biden-issuing-similar-concerns.amp.html|title=Democrats assail Trump's remarks on Germany's reliance on Russia despite Kerry, Biden issuing similar concerns|last=Mikelionis|first=Lukas|date=2018-07-13|work=Fox News|access-date=2018-07-14|language=en}}</ref> [[Chancellor of Germany|German Chancellor]] [[Angela Merkel]], who grew up in Soviet-controlled [[East Germany]], rebuffed Trump's comments and noted "I am very happy that today we are united in freedom, the Federal Republic of Germany. Because of that we can say that we can make our independent policies and make independent decisions."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/jul/11/nato-summit-donald-trump-says-germany-is-captive-of-russians|title=Angela Merkel hits back at Donald Trump at Nato summit|last=MacAskill|first=Ewen|date=2018-07-11|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-07-11}}</ref>
''The New York Times'' reported on August 9, 2018 that Trump's senior national security advisors, concerned that Trump might disrupt the summit as he did by refusing to sign the communiqué at the June [[44th G7 summit|G7 summit]], scrambled to secure a formal policy agreement during the weeks before the summit.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/09/us/politics/nato-summit-trump.html|title=U.S. Officials Scrambled Behind the Scenes to Shield NATO Deal From Trump|publisher=|accessdate=12 August 2018}}</ref>
