[[File:Monkey Buffet Lopburi 02.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.9|Monkey Buffet at Lopburi]]
The '''Monkey Buffet Festival''' is held annually in [[Lopburi]], [[Thailand]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tourism festival extremely fruitful for monkeys|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=CRAWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=bhQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3300,6438172&dq=monkey+buffet+festival|accessdate=21 June 2015|work=New Straits Times|date=1999-11-29}}</ref> In 2007, the festival included giving fruits and vegetables to the local monkey population of 2,000 in [[Lopburi Province]] north of Bangkok.<ref>{{cite news|title=Monkey Business|url=http://www.thestar.co.za/index.php?fArticleId=4145078|accessdate=21 June 2015|work=The Star|date=2007-11-26}}</ref>

The festival was described as one of the strangest festivals by London's ''Guardian'' newspaper along with Spain's [[baby-jumping festival]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Turner|first1=Lyndsey|title=From Glastonbury to tomato pelting: the festival season offers a chance to look at cultural pursuits|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2008/jun/24/learnlessonplans.secondaryschools?gusrc=rss&feed=education|accessdate=21 June 2015|work=The Guardian|date=2008-06-24}}</ref> A photograph from the Monkey Buffet Festival at Pra Prang Sam Yot temple in [[Lopburi Province]] shows a monkey trying to get at fresh fruits and vegetables embedded in blocks of ice.<ref>Sukree Sukplang [http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/object/article?f=/g/a/2007/12/01/yipnov.DTL&o=12&type=printable photograph] Reuters</ref>

