'''Richard Case Nagell''' (August 5, 1930 &ndash; November 1, 1995) is a former United States military officer who, according to Dick Russell's [[biography]] of him, claimed to have had foreknowledge of the [[assassination of President John F. Kennedy]].<ref name="ARRB">{{cite book |author=Assassination Records Review Board |authorlink1=Assassination Records Review Board |title=Final Report of the Assassination Records Review Board |url=https://www.archives.gov/research/jfk/review-board/report/arrb-final-report.pdf |format=pdf |accessdate=December 22, 2012 |date=September 30, 1998 |publisher=[[United States Government Printing Office]] |location=Washington, D.C. |pages=133-134 |chapter=Chapter 7: Pursuit of Records and Information from Non-Federal Sources|chapterurl=https://www.archives.gov/research/jfk/review-board/report/chapter-07.pdf}}</ref> According to Russell, Nagell also claimed to have gotten himself arrested in a bank shooting weeks before the assassination to avoid becoming a patsy.<ref name="Publishers Weekly">{{cite web|title=The Man Who Knew Too Much: Hired to Kill Oswald and Prevent the Assassination of JFK: Richard Case Nagell  |url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-88184-900-4 |work=[[Publishers Weekly]]|accessdate=June 23, 2014|date=November 30, 1992}}</ref> Nagell met with New Orleans District Attorney [[Jim Garrison]], who at the time was investigating [[Trial of Clay Shaw|Clay Shaw]]'s possible complicity in the assassination.<ref>Garrison, Jim. ''[[On the Trail of the Assassins]].'' New York: Sheridan Square Press, 1988. {{ISBN|0-446-36277-8}} </ref>

Nagell died from [[heart disease]] on November 1, 1995 in Los Angeles, California, one day after the Assassination Records Review Board had sent him a letter for information.<ref name="ARRB"/><ref name="Seattle Times">{{cite web| url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19951112&slug=2152132| title=Passages|work=[[The Seattle Times]]| date=1995-11-12| accessdate=2008-10-23}}</ref> He was 65 years old at the time of his death.<ref name="Seattle Times"/>

